docs.abstract: The platinum-selling country group’s new name was already being used by a blues singer. Now they’re asking a court to affirm “a trademark we have held for many years.”
docs.snippet: The platinum-selling country group’s new name was already being used by a blues singer. Now they’re asking a court to affirm “a trademark we have held for many years.”
docs.lead_paragraph: When the country trio Lady Antebellum announced last month that it would change its Civil War-referencing band name to Lady A out of respect for Black people, the group credited the widespread protests against police brutality for revealing “blind spots we didn’t even know existed.”

headline.main: Lady Antebellum Sues the Singer Lady A Over Name Change

docs.abstract: The event on Sunday will address the challenges of a music industry hit hard by the pandemic. The Weeknd, who was snubbed, says he will boycott the awards going forward, in a sign of continuing friction with artists.
docs.snippet: The event on Sunday will address the challenges of a music industry hit hard by the pandemic. The Weeknd, who was snubbed, says he will boycott the awards going forward, in a sign of continuing friction with artists.
docs.lead_paragraph: When music fans tune in to the 63rd annual Grammy Awards on Sunday night, with Trevor Noah as host and performances by nearly two dozen stars including Taylor Swift, Cardi B, Dua Lipa and BTS, they will see the music world coming together in celebration and friendly competition after a grueling year.

headline.main: Grammys Ready Pandemic Show, as the Weeknd Boycotts Future Awards​

docs.abstract: Attorney General William P. Barr’s resignation makes his low-profile deputy the nation’s top law enforcement official for President Trump’s last month.
docs.snippet: Attorney General William P. Barr’s resignation makes his low-profile deputy the nation’s top law enforcement official for President Trump’s last month.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the deputy attorney general, Jeffrey A. Rosen, testified at his confirmation hearing in April 2019, he seemed to pledge to keep politics out of law enforcement decisions, telling the Senate: “I would expect in all prosecutorial matters to proceed on the facts and the law and not any improper political influences.”

headline.main: Who Is Jeffrey Rosen, Who Will Lead the Justice Dept. for Trump’s Endgame?
headline.print_headline: Unassuming Deputy Takes Over Justice Dept. for Trump’s Final Month

docs.abstract: The film, about a jaded veteran officer and his rookie partner, plays like an amalgam of the tropes of numerous TV and movie police procedurals.
docs.snippet: The film, about a jaded veteran officer and his rookie partner, plays like an amalgam of the tropes of numerous TV and movie police procedurals.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Crown Vic” begins in the midst of a kinetic shootout, the camera zipping back and forth as a pair of masked robbers careen away from the L.A.P.D. in a car. But the writer-director Joel Souza soon dissipates the adrenaline rush of this opening into a verbose, hackneyed thriller about a night in the lives of a veteran patrol officer and his trainee.

headline.main: ‘Crown Vic’ Review: A Cop Thriller Abounding in Cliché

docs.abstract: The records had been sealed for decades, but last month, New York repealed a law keeping them secret after national protests against police brutality.
docs.snippet: The records had been sealed for decades, but last month, New York repealed a law keeping them secret after national protests against police brutality.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over 323,000 accusations of misconduct against current and former New York City police officers were published online on Thursday, a major milestone in a long and contentious political battle to open records of police discipline to public scrutiny.

docs.abstract: An irreverent “Black History Month Spectacular” arrives, on schedule but in a very different time.
docs.snippet: An irreverent “Black History Month Spectacular” arrives, on schedule but in a very different time.
docs.lead_paragraph: Juneteenth, a holiday little noticed by television in the past, has become a hopscotch square for TV networks this week as they try to calibrate their responses to protests over the killing of George Floyd. Some have hopped off, moving shows not relevant to the issues of racism and police brutality away from June 19. Many have hopped on, adding hastily assembled commemorations or other shows with African-American themes or casts, largely reruns and back-catalog documentaries.

headline.main: Review: ‘Sherman’s Showcase’ Tests Whether It’s OK to Laugh
headline.print_headline: A Show That Tests Whether It’s OK to Laugh

docs.abstract: With a Black-led production of Shakespeare’s play, an Austrian theater hopes to jump-start a conversation about racism and the need for diversity on the country’s stages.
docs.snippet: With a Black-led production of Shakespeare’s play, an Austrian theater hopes to jump-start a conversation about racism and the need for diversity on the country’s stages.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PÖLTEN, Austria — “Speak of me as I am,” Othello urges in the wrenching final scene of Shakespeare’s tragedy. Yet for centuries, those words — a plea for accurate representation — were spoken, by and large, by white actors.

headline.main: A Rare ‘Othello’ Puts the Spotlight on Race
headline.print_headline: New ‘Othello’ Puts the Spotlight on Race
